# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: neural-circuits
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] CPGs are found in humans and most other vertebrates, and in some invertebrates.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] CPG neurons can have different intrinsic membrane properties (see schematic).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Some neurons fire bursts of action potentials, either endogenously or in the presence of neuromodulatory substances.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Other neurons are bistable and generate plateau potentials that can be triggered by a depolarizing current pulse, and terminated by a hyperpolarizing current pulse.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Many CPG neurons fire after being released from inhibition (postinhibitory rebound).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Another common feature of CPG neurons is a decrease in the frequency of firing during a constant depolarization (spike frequency adaptation).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Rhythm generation in CPG networks depends on the intrinsic properties of CPG neurons and their synaptic connections.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] There are two general mechanisms for rhythm generation: pacemaker/follower and reciprocal inhibition (see schematic).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] In a network driven by a pacemaker, one or more neurons act as a core oscillator (pacemaker) that drives other, non-bursting neurons (follower) into a rhythmic pattern.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Examples of pacemaker driven networks include the pyloric rhythm of the crustacean stomatogastric ganglion and the vertebrate respiratory rhythms.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] In a network driven by reciprocal inhibition, two (groups of) neurons reciprocally inhibit each other.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Such networks are known as half-center oscillators.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The neurons are not rhythmically active when isolated, but they can produce alternating patterns of activity when coupled by inhibitory connections.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] (The neurons can also produce activity patterns of other relative phasing, including synchrony, depending on the synaptic properties).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The transitions between activated and inhibited states can occur via a number of mechanisms.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, spike-frequency adaptation in the bursting neuron(s) may slowly release the other neuron(s) from inhibition.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Reciprocal inhibition is a core feature of many CPGs, including those involved in locomotion.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Gap junctions also contribute to rhythmic oscillations and neuronal synchrony in CPGs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] They act as low-pass filter allowing slow membrane voltage fluctuations to pass more effectively across cells.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] In neonatal mice, blocking gap junctions results in decreased rhythmic activity and can completely abolish drug induced fictive locomotion.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] In zebrafish, motor neurons retrogradely control swim frequency via gap junctions.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] CPG networks have extensive recurrent synaptic connections including reciprocal excitation and reciprocal inhibition.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Synapses in CPG networks are subject to short-term activity dependent modifications.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Short-term synaptic depression and facilitation of synapses can play a role in transitions between active and inactive phases of bursting and termination of bursts.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] CPG circuits thought to be involved in the control of locomotion consist of motor neurons and spinal interneurons and are located in the lower thoracic and lumbar regions of the vertebrate spinal cord, and in each neuromere of the invertebrate ventral nerve cord.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] CPG neurons involved in swallowing are located in the brain stem, specifically the hypoglossal nucleus within the medulla.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] While the general location of CPG neurons can often be inferred, the specific location and identity of the participating neurons are only beginning to be understood.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] CPG networks are often distributed and can be flexibly reorganized, making it challenging to identify spinal interneurons.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Over the past few decades, molecular and genetic programs that control neuronal patterning have been used to specifically target spinal interneurons in mice and zebrafish.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Developing neural tube of embryonic mouse shows expression of distinct transcription factors in domains along the dorso-ventral axis of the spinal cord.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] These domains give rise to distinct population of neurons that have been classified as dorsal (dI1-dI6) and ventral (V0-V3) cardinal classes of spinal interneurons.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The ventral neurons are considered to be members of the spinal CPG network.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Each of these interneuron class can be further divided into diverse subpopulations of neurons with distinct neurotransmitter phenotype, axonal projection and function during locomotion.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, V2 interneurons are ipsilaterally projecting that can be further classified as excitatory V2a and inhibitory V2b.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] V2s are important for flexor-extensor alternation and provide excitation to motor neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Organisms must adapt their behavior to meet the needs of their internal and external environments.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Central pattern generators, as part of the neural circuitry of an organism, can be modulated to adapt to the organism's needs and surroundings.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Neuromodulatory synapses may be part of the CPG network itself.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, the CPG underlying the escape swim response in *Tritonia diomedea* contains intrinsic neuromodulatory neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] These neuromodulatory neurons can enhance neurotransmitter release from another neuron in the circuit and its neuromodulatory actions are thought to be important for producing swim motor program.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Neuromodulatory inputs can also activate CPG networks and can be necessary for generation of rhythmic output.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Loss of neuromodulatory inputs can abolish rhythmic activity from pyloric network.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] In vertebrates, application of neuromodulators have been shown to evoke locomotor activity.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Neuromodulators can alter the synaptic strength as well as intrinsic properties of neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] These actions can alter the frequency and the phase relationships between neurons and thereby change the output pattern of the circuit.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, exogenous application of various neuromodulators can elicit triphasic motor pattern in the STG where each modulator results in generation of a different motor pattern.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Neuromodulatory projections expressing a common modulator can also elicit different patterns from the same network.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Stimulation of different proctolin-containing projection neurons in the STG results in a distinct motor pattern from the same network due to differences in cotransmitter complement of these projection neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The effects of neuromodulators are distributed throughout the CPG network.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Specially, dopamine was shown to affect cellular and synaptic properties of nearly all components of the crustacean pyloric network.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Moreover, dopamine can have opposing effects on different components of the network.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] As such, the final output of the network reflects a combination of modulatory actions on individual components.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Neuronal composition of CPGs can vary with the state of the system.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Neuromodulators can activate or inhibit neurons of the CPGs and can even combine different networks into one.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, in the lobster stomatogastric nervous system the neuropeptide, red pigment concentrating hormone, can strengthen synapses between two different networks to create a single, combined rhythm.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Neuromodulators can also result in switching of neurons from one network to another.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Although the theory of central pattern generation calls for basic rhythmicity and patterning to be centrally generated, CPGs can respond to sensory feedback to alter the patterning in behaviorally appropriate ways.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Alteration of the pattern is difficult because feedback received during only one phase may require changed movement in the other parts of the patterned cycle to preserve certain coordination relationships.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, walking with a pebble in the right shoe alters the entire gait, even though the stimulus is only present while standing on the right foot.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Even during the time when the left foot is down and the sensory feedback is inactive, action is taken to prolong the right leg swing and extend the time on the left foot, leading to limping.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This effect could be due to widespread and long-lasting effects of the sensory feedback on the CPG or due to short-term effects on a few neurons that in turn modulate nearby neurons and spread the feedback through the entire CPG in that way.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Some degree of modulation is required to allow one CPG to assume multiple states in response to feedback.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Additionally, the effect of the sensory input varies depending on the phase of the pattern in which it occurs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, during walking, resistance to the top of the swinging foot (e.g., by a horizontal stick) causes the foot to be lifted higher to move over the stick.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] However, the same input to the standing foot cannot cause the foot to lift or the person would collapse.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Thus, depending on the phase, the same sensory input can cause the foot to be lifted higher or held more firmly to the ground.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] "This change in motor response as a function of motor pattern phase is called reflex reversal, and has been observed in invertebrates (DiCaprio and Clarac, 1981) and vertebrates (Forssberg et al., 1977).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] How this process occurs is poorly understood, but again two possibilities exist.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] One is that sensory input is appropriately routed to different CPG neurons as a function of motor pattern phase.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] A study by Gottschall and Nichols examined the hindlimb of a decerebrate cat during walking (a CPG controlled function) in response to changes in head pitch.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This study describes the differences in gait and body position of cats walking uphill, downhill and on level surfaces.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Proprioceptive (Golgi tendon organs and muscle spindles) and exteroreceptive (optic, vestibular and cutaneous) receptors work alone or in combination to adjust the CPG to sensory feedback.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The study explored the effects of neck proprioceptors (giving information about the relative location of the head and body) and vestibular receptors (giving information about the orientation of the head relative to gravity).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Decerebrate cats were made to walk on a level surface with their heads level, tilted up or tilted down.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Comparing the decerebrate cats to normal cats showed similar EMG patterns during level walking and EMG patterns that reflected downhill walking with the head titled up and uphill walking with the head tilted down.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This study proved that neck proprioceptors and vestibular receptors contribute sensory feedback that alters the gait of the animal.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This information may be useful for treatment of gait disorders.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Central pattern generators can serve many functions.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] CPGs can play roles in movement, breathing, rhythm generation and other oscillatory functions.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Below are several key functions of CPGs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] As early as 1911, it was recognized, by the experiments of Thomas Graham Brown, that the basic pattern of stepping can be produced by the spinal cord without the need of descending commands from the cortex.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The first modern evidence of the central pattern generator was produced by isolating the locust nervous system and showing that it could produce a rhythmic output in isolation resembling that of the locust in flight.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Since that time, evidence has arisen for the presence of central pattern generators in vertebrate animals, starting with work on the cat in the 1960s by Elzbieta Jankowska in Gothenburg, who provided the first evidence for a spinal cord CPG.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This section addresses the role of the central pattern generator in locomotion for the lamprey and humans.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The lamprey has been used as a model for vertebrate CPGs because, while its nervous system has a vertebrate organization, it shares many positive characteristics with invertebrates.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] When removed from the lamprey, the intact spinal cord can survive for days *in vitro*.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] It also has very few neurons and can be easily stimulated to produce a fictive swimming motion indicative of a central pattern generator.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The different movements have been found to be altered by neuromodulators, including serotonin in a study by Harris-Warrick and Cohen in 1985 and tachykinin in a study by Parker et al. in 1998.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The lamprey model of CPG for locomotion has been important to the study of CPGs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Although Sten Grillner claims that the locomotor network is characterised, a claim that has seemingly been uncritically accepted by the spinal cord locomotor network field, there are in fact many missing details and Grillner cannot provide the evidence he uses to support his claims (Parker 2006).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] A general scheme of the lamprey CPG is now being used in the creation of artificial CPGs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, Ijspeert and Kodjabachian used Ekeberg's model for the lamprey to create artificial CPGs and simulate swimming movements in a lamprey-like substrate using controllers based on a SGOCE encoding.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Essentially, these are the first steps toward the use of CPGs to code for locomotion in robots.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The vertebrate model of CPG has been also developed with both Hodgkin-Huxley formalism, its variants and control system approaches.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, Yakovenko and colleagues have developed a simple mathematical model that describes basic principles proposed by T.G.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Brown with integrate-to-threshold units organized with mutually inhibitory connections.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This model is sufficient to describe complex properties of behavior, such as different regimes of the extensor- and flexor-dominant locomotion observed during electrical stimulation of the mesencephalic locomotor region (MLR), MLR-induced fictive locomotion.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The connections between the CPGs that control each limb manage interlimb coordination and hence the gaits in quadrupedal and possibly also bipedal animals.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Left right coordination is mediated by commissural and fore-hind as well as diagonal coordination is mediated by long-projecting propiospinal interneurons.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This balance changes with increasing speed, potentially because of modulation by supraspinal drive from the MLR and mediated by the reticular formation, and causes speed dependent gait transitions characteristic for quadrupedal animals.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Commissural and long propriospinal neurons are a likely target of supraspinal and somatosensory afferent inputs to adjust interlimb coordination and gait to different environmental and behavioral conditions.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Central pattern generators also contribute to locomotion in humans.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] In 1994, Calancie, et al. described the "first well-defined example of a central rhythm generator for stepping in the adult human." The subject was a 37-year-old male who suffered an injury to the cervical spinal cord 17 years prior.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] After initial total paralysis below the neck, the subject eventually regained some movement of the arms and fingers and limited movement in the lower limbs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] He had not recovered sufficiently to support his own weight.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] After 17 years, the subject found that when lying supine and extending his hips, his lower extremities underwent step-like movements for as long as he remained lying down.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] When tonic electrical stimulation is applied to these fibers in motor complete spinal cord injured individuals (i.e., individuals in whom the spinal cord is functionally isolated from the brain) rhythmic, locomotor-like movement of the lower limbs can be elicited.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] These measurements were performed in supine position, thus minimizing peripheral feedback.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Subsequent studies showed that these lumbar locomotor centers can form a large variety of rhythmic movements by combining and distributing stereotypical patterns to the numerous lower limb muscles.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] A CPG-activating drug treatment called Spinalon, active centrally upon oral administration, has also been shown to partially reactivate spinal locomotor neurons in complete or motor-complete spinal cord-injured patients.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Preliminary evidence of efficacy was also found using videotape and electromyographic recordings since doses below MTD could acutely induce rhythmic locomotor-like leg movements in groups with Spinalon, but not in those with placebo (cornstarch).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] If step cycle durations and muscle activations were fixed, it would not be possible to change body velocity and adapt to varying terrain.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] It has been suggested that the mammalian locomotor CPG comprises a "timer" (possibly in the form of coupled oscillators) which generates step cycles of varying durations, and a "pattern formation layer," which selects and grades the activation of motor pools.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Increasing the neural drive from the midbrain locomotor region (MLR) to the spinal CPG increases the step cycle frequency (the cadence).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Swing and stance phase durations co-vary in a fairly fixed relationship, with stance phases changing more than swing phases.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Sensory input from the limbs may truncate or extend individual phase durations in a process akin to finite state control (in which "if-then" rules determine when state transitions occur).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, if a limb that is swinging forward reaches the end of swing in less time than the current CPG-generated flexor phase duration, sensory input would cause the CPG timer to terminate swing and start the stance phase.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Furthermore, as body velocity increases, the pattern formation layer would increase muscle activation nonlinearly to provide increased load-bearing and thrust forces.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] It has been posited that in well-predicted movements, CPG-generated phase durations and muscle forces closely match those required by the evolving biomechanical events, minimizing the sensory corrections required.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The term "neuromechanical tuning" has been coined to describe this process.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] 1 provides a simplified schematic that summarizes these proposed mechanisms.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] A command specifying desired body velocity descends from higher centers to the MLR, which drives the spinal locomotor CPG.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The CPG timer produces the appropriate cadence and phase durations and the pattern formation layer modulates the motoneuronal outputs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The activated muscles resist stretch through their own intrinsic biomechanical properties, providing a rapid form of length and velocity feedback control.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Reflexes mediated by Golgi tendon organ and other afferents provide additional load compensation, but the main role of sensory input may be to adjust or override the CPG at stance-swing-stance transitions.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] As described in Neuromodulation, the human locomotive CPG is very adaptable and can respond to sensory input.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] It receives input from the brainstem as well as from the environment to keep the network regulated.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Newer studies have not only confirmed the presence of the CPG for human locomotion, but also confirmed its robustness and adaptability.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, Choi and Bastian showed that the networks responsible for human walking are adaptable on short and long timescales.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] They showed adaptation to different gait patterns and different walking contexts.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Also, they showed that different motor patterns can adapt independently.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Adults could even walk on treadmills going in a different direction for each leg.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This study showed that independent networks control forward and backward walking and that networks controlling each leg can adapt independently and be trained to walk independently.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Thus, humans also possess a central pattern generator for locomotion that is capable not only of rhythmic pattern generation but also remarkable adaptation and usefulness in a wide variety of situations.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] A three-phase model is the classical view of the respiratory CPG.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The rhythmicity of these nerves is classically viewed as originating from a single rhythm generator.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] In this model, phasing is produced by reciprocal synaptic inhibition between groups of sequentially active interneurons.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Nevertheless, an alternative model has been proposed reinforced by certain experimental data.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] According to this model, respiratory rhythm is generated by two coupled anatomically distinct rhythm generators, one in the pre-Boetzinger complex and the other in the retrotrapezoid nucleus / parafacial respiratory group.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Further survey provided evidence to the hypothesis that one of the networks is responsible for inspiration rhythm and the other for expiration rhythm.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Therefore, inspiration and expiration are distinct functions and one does not induce the other, as is the common belief, but one of two dominates the behavior by generating a faster rhythm.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Swallowing involves the coordinated contraction of more than 25 pairs of muscles in the oropharynx, larynx and esophagus, which are active during an oropharyngeal phase, followed by the primary esophageal peristalsis.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Neurons in the DSG are responsible for the generation of the swallowing pattern, while those in the VSG distribute the commands to the various motoneuronal pools.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] As in other CPGs, the functioning of the central network can be modulated by peripheral and central inputs, so that the swallowing pattern is adapted to the size of the bolus.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Within this network, central inhibitory connections play a major role, producing a rostrocaudal inhibition that parallels the rostrocaudal anatomy of the swallowing tract.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Thus, when the neurons controlling the proximal parts of the tract are active, those that command more distal parts are inhibited.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Apart from the type of connection between the neurons, intrinsic properties of the neurons, especially those of NTS neurons, probably also contribute to the shaping and timing of the swallowing pattern.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This means that at least some of the swallowing neurons may be multifunctional neurons and belong to pools of neurons that are common to several CPGs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] One such CPG is the respiratory one, which has been observed interacting with the swallowing CPG.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Central pattern generators can also play a role in rhythm generation for other functions in vertebrates.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, the rat vibrissa system uses an unconventional CPG for whisking movements.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] "Like other CPGs, the whisking generator can operate without cortical input or sensory feedback.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] However, unlike other CPGs, vibrissa motoneurons actively participate in **rhythmogenesis** by converting tonic serotonergic inputs into the patterned motor output responsible for movement of the vibrissae." Breathing is another non-locomotive function of central pattern generators.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, larval amphibians accomplish gas exchange largely through rhythmic ventilation of the gills.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] A study showed that lung ventilation in the tadpole brainstem may be driven by a pacemaker-like mechanism, whereas the respiratory CPG adapts in the adult bullfrog as it matures.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Thus, CPGs hold a broad range of functions in the vertebrate animal and are widely adaptable and variable with age, environment and behavior.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Rhythmicity in CPGs can also result from time-dependent cellular properties such as adaptation, delayed excitation, and post-inhibitory rebound (PIR).
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] PIR is an intrinsic property that elicits rhythmic electrical activity by depolarizing the membrane once hyperpolarizing stimulus is gone.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] It can be produced by several mechanisms including hyperpolarization-activated cation current (Ih), low-voltage activated calcium current, or deinactivation of depolarization-activated inward currents.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Once inhibition has ceased, this period of PIR can be explained as the time with increased neuronal excitability.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] It is the property of many CNS neurons that sometimes results in action potential "bursts" following immediately after inhibitory synaptic input.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] "Because of this, it has been suggested that PIR may contribute to the maintenance of oscillatory activity in neural networks that are characterized by mutual inhibitory connections, like those involved in locomotor behaviors.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] In addition, PIR is often included as an element in computational models of neural networks that involve mutual inhibition".
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, the "PIR in crayfish stretch receptor neurons is caused by recovery from adaptation during the course of inhibitory hyperpolarization.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] One feature of that system is that PIR only occurs if the hyperpolarization is imposed on a background of excitation, caused in this case by stretch.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] They also found that PIR can be elicited in the stretch receptor by hyperpolarizing current pulses.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] This was an important finding because it showed that PIR is an intrinsic property of the postsynaptic neuron, related to the membrane potential change associated with inhibition but independent of transmitter receptors or presynaptic properties.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The latter conclusion has stood the test of time, marking PIR as a robust property of CNS neurons in a wide variety of contexts." This cellular property can most easily be seen in the Lamprey neural circuit.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] The swimming movement is produced by alternating neural activity between the left and right side of the body, causing it to bend back and forth while creating oscillating movements.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] While the Lamprey is bent to the left, there is reciprocal inhibition on the right side causing it to relax due to hyperpolarization.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Immediately after this hyperopolarizing stimulus, the interneurons use post-inhibitory rebound to initiate activity in the right side.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Depolarization of the membrane causes it to contract while reciprocal inhibition is now applied to the left side.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] CPGs play a similarly critical role in coordinating behaviors in invertebrates, and studying invertebrate CPGs with fewer numbers of neurons has helped establish general principles of CPGs and their organization in the nervous system.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] One model circuit for studying CPGs is the stomatogastric ganglion in crabs and lobsters, a ~30 neuron circuit containing two CPGs that generate rhythmic motor output for chewing and digesting food.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Dissection of these circuits has revealed neural mechanisms of CPGs.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] For example, the pyloric CPG - which controls the contraction and dilation of the pylorus - contains a set of conditional oscillatory neurons and one pacemaker neuron that fires rhythmically when dissected out of the circuit.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Coordinated rhythmic behaviors like walking, flight and grooming are also controlled by CPGs in some invertebrates.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Continued research into how CPGs control these behaviors has revealed a nested CPG architecture to control rhythmic behaviors across various timescales.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Other examples of CPGs in invertebrate animals include a CPG modulating reflexive withdrawal, escape swimming and crawling in the mollusc *Tritonia,* and to control the heartbeat of leeches.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Central pattern generators play a broad role in all animals and show amazing variability and adaptability in almost all cases.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] One theory that reconciles the role of sensory feedback during rhythmic locomotion is to redefine CPGs as "state estimators" as opposed to rhythm generators.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Through this perspective, CPGs are an intrinsic spinal processor that corrects imperfect sensory feedback and adapts central input to this optimized peripheral input.
[src:neural-circuits/central-pattern-generator] Models using this framework are able to accomplish rhythmic behavior as well as fictive locomotion without incorporating independent rhythm generators.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] A **connectome** (/kəˈnɛktoʊm/) is a comprehensive map of neural connections in the brain, and may be thought of as its "wiring diagram".
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] These maps are available in varying levels of detail.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] A **functional connectome** shows connections between various brain regions, but not individual neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] These are available for large animals, including mice and humans, are normally obtained by techniques such as MRI, and have a scale of millimeters.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] At the other extreme are **neural connectomes**, which show individual neurons and their interconnections.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] These are usually obtained by electron microscopy (EM) and have a scale of nanometers.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] They are only available for small creatures such as the worm *C. elegans* and the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster*, and small regions of mammal brains.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Finally there are **chemical connectomes**, showing which neurons emit, and are sensitive to, a wide variety of neuromodulators.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] As of 2025, only *C. elegans* has such a connectome.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The significance of the connectome stems from the realization that the structure and function of any brain are intricately linked, through multiple levels and modes of brain connectivity.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] There are strong natural constraints on which neurons or neural populations can interact, or how strong or direct their interactions are.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Indeed, the foundation of human cognition lies in the pattern of dynamic interactions shaped by the connectome.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Despite such complex and variable structure-function mappings, connectomes are an indispensable basis for the mechanistic interpretation of dynamic brain data, from single-cell recordings to functional neuroimaging.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The terms *connectome* and *connectomics* were introduced independently by Olaf Sporns at Indiana University and Patric Hagmann at Lausanne University Hospital to refer to a map of the neural connections within the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] This term was directly inspired by the ongoing effort to sequence the human genetic code—to build a genome.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] It was more recently popularized by Sebastian Seung's *I am my Connectome* speech given at the 2010 TED conference.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] In 2012, Seung published the book *Connectome: How the Brain's Wiring Makes Us Who We Are*.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Brain networks can be defined at different levels of scale, corresponding to levels of spatial resolution in brain imaging.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] These scales can be roughly categorized as macroscale, mesoscale and microscale.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Ultimately, it may be possible to join connectomic maps obtained at different scales into a single hierarchical map of the neural organization of a given species that ranges from single neurons to populations of neurons to larger systems like cortical areas.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Given the methodological uncertainties involved in inferring connectivity from the primary experimental data, and given that there are likely to be large differences in the connectomes of different individuals, any unified map will likely rely on *probabilistic* representations of connectivity data.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] A connectome at the macroscale (millimeter resolution) attempts to capture large brain systems that can be parcellated into anatomically distinct modules (areas, parcels or nodes), each having a distinct pattern of connectivity.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Connectomic databases at the mesoscale and macroscale may be significantly more compact than those at cellular resolution, but they require effective strategies for accurate anatomical or functional parcellation of the neural volume into network nodes.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Established methods of brain research, such as axonal tracing, provided early avenues for building connectome data sets.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] However, more recent advances in living subjects has been made by the use of non-invasive imaging technologies such as diffusion-weighted magnetic resonance imaging (DW-MRI) and functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI).
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The first, when combined with tractography allows reconstruction of the major fiber bundles in the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The second allows the researcher to capture the brain's network activity (either at rest or while performing directed tasks), enabling the identification of structurally and anatomically distinct areas of the brain that are functionally connected.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Notably, the goal of the Human Connectome Project, led by the WU-Minn consortium, was to build a *structural and functional map* of the healthy human brain at the macro scale, using a combination of multiple imaging technologies and resolutions.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Throughout the 2000s, several investigators have attempted to map the large-scale structural architecture of the human cerebral cortex.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] One attempt exploited cross-correlations in cortical thickness or volume across individuals.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Such gray-matter thickness correlations have been postulated as indicators for the presence of structural connections.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] A drawback of the approach is that it provides highly indirect information about cortical connection patterns and requires data from large numbers of individuals to derive a single connection data set across a subject group.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Other investigators have attempted to build whole-brain connection matrices from DW-MRI imaging data.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The Blue Brain Project attempted to reconstruct the entire mouse connectome using a diamond knife sharpened to an atomic edge, and electron microscopy for imaging tissue slices.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] They ended up in 2018 with an atlas providing information about major cell types, numbers, and positions in 737 regions of the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The initial explorations in macroscale human connectomics were done using either equally sized regions or anatomical regions with unclear relationship to the underlying functional organization of the brain (e.g. gyral and sulcal-based regions).
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] While much can be learned from these approaches, it is highly desirable to parcellate the brain into functionally distinct parcels: brain regions with distinct architectonics, connectivity, function, and/or topography.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Accurate parcellation allows each node in the macroscale connectome to be more informative by associating it with a distinct connectivity pattern and functional profile.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Parcellation of localized areas of cortex have been accomplished using diffusion tractography and functional connectivity to non-invasively measure connectivity patterns and define cortical areas based on distinct connectivity patterns.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Such analyses may best be done on a whole brain scale and by integrating non-invasive modalities.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Accurate whole brain parcellation may lead to more accurate macroscale connectomes for the normal brain, which can then be compared to disease states.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Pathways through cerebral white matter can be charted by histological dissection and staining, by degeneration methods, and by axonal tracing.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Axonal tracing methods form the primary basis for the systematic charting of long-distance pathways into extensive, species-specific anatomical connection matrices between gray matter regions.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Landmark studies have included the areas and connections of the visual cortex of the macaque and the thalamocortical system in the feline brain.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The development of neuroinformatics databases for anatomical connectivity allow for continual updating and refinement of such anatomical connection maps.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The online macaque cortex connectivity tool CoCoMac and the temporal lobe connectome of the rat are prominent examples of such a database.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Nerve cells communicate with adjacent cells through synapses and gap junctions, but they also communicate with distant cells via chemicals (typically neuropeptides) that diffuse through tissue and trigger receptors on cells far away.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] There are hundreds of such neuromodulators, with any given nerve cell emitting and responding to at most as few of them.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The graph that describes these interactions is another form of connectome.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The largest (and only, as of 2025), animal with a complete chemical connectome is *C. elegans*, although there is preliminary work in other animals.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Mapping the connectome at the "microscale" (micrometer resolution) means building a complete map of the neural systems, neuron-by-neuron.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] This is (barely) possible for small animals such as worms or flies (for example, see Drosophila connectome) but the challenge of doing this in more complex organisms becomes obvious: the number of neurons comprising the brain easily ranges into the billions.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The human cerebral cortex alone contains on the order of 9×1010 neurons linked by 1014 synaptic connections.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] By comparison, the number of base-pairs in a human genome is 3×109.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] To address the data collection issues, several groups are building high-throughput serial electron microscopes.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] To address the machine-vision and image-processing issues, the Open Connectome Project is *alg-sourcing* (algorithm outsourcing) this hurdle.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Finally, statistical graph theory is an emerging discipline which is developing sophisticated pattern recognition and inference tools to parse these brain-graphs.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Current non-invasive imaging techniques cannot capture the brain's activity on a neuron-by-neuron level, except for small animals that are optically transparent (such as Danionella and larval zebrafish).
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Mapping the connectome at the cellular level in larger vertebrates currently requires post-mortem (after death) microscopic analysis of limited portions of brain tissue.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Non-optical techniques that rely on high-throughput DNA sequencing have been proposed by Anthony Zador (CSHL).
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Each of these classical approaches has specific drawbacks when it comes to deployment for connectomics.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The staining of single cells, e.g. with the Golgi stain, to trace cellular processes and connectivity suffers from the limited resolution of light-microscopy as well as difficulties in capturing long-range projections.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Tract tracing, often described as the "gold standard" of neuroanatomy for detecting long-range pathways across the brain, generally only allows the tracing of fairly large cell populations and single axonal pathways.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] EM reconstruction was successfully used for the compilation of the *C. elegans* connectome, and has recently (as of 2025) been extended, using considerable application of time, money, and personnel, to the entire nervous system of fruit flies.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] However, applications to larger tissue blocks of entire nervous systems have traditionally had difficulty with projections that span longer distances.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] In March 2011, the journal *Nature* published a pair of articles on micro-connectomes: Bock et al. and Briggman et al.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] In both articles, the authors first characterized the functional properties of a small subset of cells, and then manually traced a subset of the processes emanating from those cells to obtain a partial subgraph.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] In alignment with the principles of open science, the authors of Bock et al.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] (2011) have released their data for public access.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The full resolution 12 terabyte dataset from Bock et al. is available at *NeuroData*.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Independently, important topologies of functional interactions among several hundred cells are also gradually going to be declared.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] In 2016, the Intelligence Advanced Research Projects Activity of the United States government launched MICrONS, a five-year, multi-institute project to map one cubic millimeter of rodent visual cortex, as part of the BRAIN Initiative.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Though only a small volume of biological tissue, this project will yield one of the largest micro-scale connectomics datasets currently in existence.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Alternative techniques for mapping neural connectivity at the cellular level offer significant new hope for overcoming the limitations of classical techniques and for compiling cellular connectome data sets.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Using Brainbow, a combinatorial color labeling method based on the stochastic expression of several fluorescent proteins, Jeff W.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Lichtman and colleagues were able to mark individual neurons with one of over 100 distinct colors.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The labeling of individual neurons with a distinguishable hue then allows the tracing and reconstruction of their cellular structure including long processes within a block of tissue.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Another alternative approach to EM for to mapping connectivity was proposed in 2012 by Zador and colleagues.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Zador's technique, called BOINC (barcoding of individual neuronal connections) uses high-throughput DNA sequencing to map neural circuits.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Briefly, the approach consists of labelling each neuron with a unique DNA barcode, transferring barcodes between synaptically coupled neurons (for example using *Suid herpesvirus 1*, SuHV1), and fusion of barcodes to represent a synaptic pair.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] This approach has the potential to be cheap, fast, and extremely high-throughput.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] In 2022, a new technique called LICONN combined hydrogel expansion with light microscopy (as opposed to electron microscopy) to generate neuron level connectomes.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The chief advantages are cheaper equipment (optical vs EM microscopes), faster data acquisition, and multi-color labelling.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] At the beginning of the connectome project, it was thought that the connections between neurons were unchangeable once established and that only individual synapses could be altered.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] However, evidence suggests that connectivity is also subject to change, termed neuroplasticity.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] There are two ways that the brain can rewire: formation and removal of synapses in an established connection or formation or removal of entire connections between neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Connectomics have been used to assess brain states in both health and disease.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Moreover, connectome-based methods have had an impact on planning or understanding therapeutic options, such as invasive and noninvasive brain stimulation procedures.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] In this context, the term 'connectomic surgery' was introduced in 2012, as a framework to define or refine surgical targets by identifying pathological brain circuits using neuroimaging techniques such as diffusion-imaging based tractography that are also leveraged for macroscale connectomics.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Once identified, dysfunctional circuits may be lesioned by means of ablative neurosurgery or disrupted by means of deep brain stimulation.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The (hypothetical) complete library that maps dysfunctional circuits onto specific neurological or psychiatric symptoms has been termed the 'dysfunctome' of the human brain, which could be iteratively mapped and used to inform interventional brain circuit therapeutics.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] For macroscacle connectomes, the most common research subject is the human.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] For microscale connectomes, the most common subjects are the nematode *C. elegans*, the fruit fly, the mouse, and the barn owl.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The Human Connectome Project (HCP) was an initiative launched in 2009 by the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to map the neural pathways that underlie human brain function.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The goal was to obtain and distribute information regarding the structural and functional connections within the human brain, improving imaging and analysis methods to enhance resolution and practicality in the realm of connectomics.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] By understanding the wiring patterns within and across individuals, researchers hope to unravel the electrical signals that give rise to our thoughts, emotions, and behaviors.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Additional programs within the Connectome Initiative, such as the Lifespan Connectome and Disease Connectome, focus on mapping brain connections across different age groups and studying connectome variations in individuals with specific clinical diagnoses.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The Connectome Coordination Facility serves as a centralized repository for HCP data and provides support to researchers.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The success of this project has opened the door to understanding how connectomics might be influential in other areas of neuroscience.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The potential of a "Connectome II" project has been referenced recently, which would focus on developing a scanner designed for high-throughput studies involving multiple subjects.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The project would aim to utilize recent advancements in visualization technologies towards a higher spatial resolution in imaging structural connectivity.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Advancements in this area might also involve incorporating wearable mobile technology to acquire various types of behavioral data, complementing the neuroimaging information gathered by the scanner.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The *C. elegans* connectome reconstruction began with manual annotation of electron micrographs, published by White, Brenner et al., in 1986.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Based on this seminal work, the first ever connectome (then called "neural circuitry database" by the authors) for *C. elegans* was published in book form with accompanying floppy disks by Achacoso and Yamamoto in 1992.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The very first paper on the computer representation of its connectome was presented and published three years earlier in 1989 by Achacoso at the Symposium on Computer Application in Medical Care (SCAMC).
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The *C. elegans* connectome was later revised.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The small size of the nervous system of *C. elegans* has allowed studies that would be difficult or impractical in larger organisms.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] These include changes during the animal's development., variability between individuals, both at the level of synapse and connection, despite an invariant cell lineage and changes during development and aging.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Researchers found the biggest change with age is the wiring circuits, and that connectivity between and within brain regions increases with age.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Other studies have combined the connectome with behavior, environmental influences, and other available information to study the connection between neuroanatomy and behavior, and suggested comparing the connectome to that of other animals, once available.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Two other small animals with complete connectomes are the larvi of the ascidian *Ciona intestinalis* (177 CNS neurons, 6618 synapses including 1772 neuromuscular junctions and 1206 gap junctions) and *Platynereis dumerilii* (2728 neurons, 25,509 synapses).
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The fruit fly, *Drosophila melanogaster*, serves as an appealing model for exploring the structure and operation of nervous systems.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Its central nervous system (CNS) is notably compact, housing approximately 3,000 neurons in the larva and 200,000 neurons in adults, and the fly exhibits reasonably stereotyped neural connections across individual flies.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Despite its small size, this CNS supports a broad spectrum of complex and well-studied behaviors, plus there are many genetic tools that enable experiments on the CNS.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Obtaining an anatomical dataset of the fly's CNS could be a pivotal step, potentially offering insights into the nervous systems of other organisms.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Within the last decade, largely owing to technological advancements in EM data collection and image processing, multiple synapse-scale connectome datasets have been generated for the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* in its adult and larval forms.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] There are also currently two publicly available datasets of the adult fly ventral nerve cord (VNC).
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The female adult nerve cord (FANC) was collected using high-throughput ssTEM by Wei-Chung Allen Lee's lab at Harvard Medical School. and was further reconstructed in 2024.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The male adult nerve cord (MANC) was reconstructed soon after.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] In addition, the connectome of a complete central nervous system (connected brain and VNC) of a 1st instar *D. melanogaster* larva has been reconstructed as a single dataset of 3016 neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Progress is still on-going - as of 2025, two teams have reported complete adult CNS connectomes that includes both the brain and the VNC, in both male and female flies.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Partial connectomes of a mouse retina and mouse primary visual cortex are available.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] The first full connectome of a mammalian circuit (not the whole brain) was constructed in 2021.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] This construction included the development of all connections between the central nervous system and a single muscle from birth to adulthood.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] An online database known as *MouseLight* displays over 1000 neurons mapped in the mouse brain based on a collective database of sub-micron resolution images of these brains.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] This platform illustrates the thalamus, hippocampus, cerebral cortex, and hypothalamus based on single-cell projections.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Imaging technology to produce this mouse brain does not allow an in-depth look at synapses but can show axonal arborizations which contain many synapses.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] A limiting factor to studying mouse connectomes, much like with humans, is the complexity of labeling all the cell types of the mouse brain; this is a process that would require the reconstruction of 100,000+ neurons and imaging technology is not yet advanced enough to do so.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Some portions of the technology needed to scale ultrastructural circuit mapping to the whole mouse brain are under investigation.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] However, the mouse brain is about 10,000 times bigger than the *Drosophila* brain, the largest reconstructed as of 2025.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] A mouse connectome will therefore require non-trivial advances in connectivity mapping.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] Eyewire is an online game developed by American scientist Sebastian Seung of Princeton University.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] It uses social computing to help map the connectome of the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/connectome] It has attracted over 130,000 players from over 100 countries.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] A **cortical column** is a group of neurons forming a cylindrical structure through the cerebral cortex of the brain perpendicular to the cortical surface.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The structure was first identified by Rafael Lorente de Nó in 1949 while Vernon Benjamin Mountcastle began to disentangle its physiology in 1957.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] He later identified minicolumns as the basic units of the neocortex which were arranged into columns.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Each contains the same types of neurons, connectivity, and firing properties.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Columns are also called **hypercolumn**, **macrocolumn**, **functional column** or sometimes **cortical module**.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Neurons within a minicolumn (microcolumn) encode similar features, whereas a hypercolumn "denotes a unit containing a full set of values for any given set of receptive field parameters".
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] A cortical module is defined as either synonymous with a hypercolumn or as a tissue block of multiple overlapping hypercolumns.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Cortical columns are proposed to be the canonical microcircuits for predictive coding, in which the process of cognition is implemented through a hierarchy of identical microcircuits.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The evolutionary benefit to this duplication allowed human neocortex to increase in size by almost 3-fold over just the last 3 million years.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The columnar hypothesis states that the cortex is composed of discrete, modular columns of neurons, characterized by a consistent connectivity profile.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The columnar organization hypothesis is currently the most widely adopted to explain the cortical processing of information.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The mammalian cerebral cortex, the grey matter encapsulating the white matter, is composed of layers.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The human cortex is between 2 and 3 mm thick.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The number of layers is the same in most mammals, but varies throughout the cortex.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] 6 layers can be recognized in the neocortex, although many regions lack one or more layers.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] For example, fewer layers are present in the archipallium and the paleopallium.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The 6 layer model of the cerebral cortex defines layers by frequency of cell type.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Layer 1 (L1), called the molecular layer, lies in the most superior in the cortex and mainly contains dendrites, axons, and axon terminals.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] L2 and L3 lie just underneath L1 and both layers contain pyramidal cells, with the size of these cells increasing in the deepest part of L3.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] L2 and L3 pyramidal axons project to both local and non-local cortical areas.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] L4, termed the granular layer, is generally responsible for receiving signals from the thalamus, therefore controlling the sensory input of many different cortical areas.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] L4 is composed of mostly small spherical neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] L5 is the most inferior layer composed of pyramidal cells.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The large pyramidal cells in L5 are responsible for large outputs to subcortical and other cortical areas.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] L6 is multiform and generally consists of axon projections between structures.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Cortical columns are viewed as vertical projections of cells in these layers.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The columnar functional organization, as originally framed by Vernon Mountcastle, suggests that neurons that are horizontally more than 0.5 mm (500 μm) from each other do not have overlapping sensory receptive fields, and other experiments give similar results: 200–800 μm.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Various estimates suggest there are 50 to 100 cortical minicolumns in a hypercolumn, each comprising around 80 neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] An important distinction is that the columnar organization is functional by definition, and reflects the local connectivity of the cerebral cortex.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Connections "up" and "down" within the thickness of the cortex are much denser than connections that spread from side to side.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] David Hubel and Torsten Wiesel followed up on Mountcastle's discoveries in the somatic sensory cortex with their own studies in vision.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] A part of the discoveries that resulted in them winning the 1981 Nobel Prize was that there were cortical columns in vision as well, and that the neighboring columns were also related in function in terms of the orientation of lines that evoked the maximal discharge.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Hubel and Wiesel followed up on their own studies with work demonstrating the impact of environmental changes on cortical organization, and the sum total of these works resulted in their Nobel Prize.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The visual studies done by Hubel and Wiesel defined **ocular dominance** (OD) columns.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Sometimes referred to as OD stripes, these columns in the visual cortex are groups of neurons that respond to stimulation in either eye.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] While some columns cannot be defined anatomically because they are so close together, the extensive studies of Hubel and Weisel showed that visual columns can be defined anatomically and physiologically.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] There are about 200 million (2×108) cortical minicolumns in the human neocortex with up to about 110 neurons each, and with estimates of 21–26 billion (2.1×1010–2.6×1010) neurons in the neocortex.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] With 50 to 100 cortical minicolumns per cortical column a human would have 2–4 million (2×106–4×106) cortical columns.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] There may be more if the columns can overlap, as suggested by Tsunoda *et al*.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Jeff Hawkins claims that there are only 150,000 columns in the human neocortex, based on research made by his company Numenta.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] There are claims that minicolumns may have as many as 400 principal cells, but it is not clear if that includes glia cells.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Some contradict the previous estimates, claiming the original research is too arbitrary.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The authors propose a uniform neocortex, and choose a fixed width and length to calculate the cell numbers.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] Later research pointed out that the neocortex is indeed not uniform for other species, and studying nine primate species they found that "the number of neurons underneath 1 mm2 of the cerebral cortical surface ... varies by three times across species." The neocortex is not uniform across species.
[src:neural-circuits/cortical-column] The actual number of neurons within a single column is variable, and depends on the cerebral areas and thus the function of the column.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] In neurobiology, **lateral inhibition** is the capacity of an excited neuron to reduce the activity of its neighbors.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Lateral inhibition disables the spreading of action potentials from excited neurons to neighboring neurons in the lateral direction.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] This creates a contrast in stimulation that allows increased sensory perception.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] It is also referred to as lateral antagonism and occurs primarily in visual processes, but also in tactile, auditory, and even olfactory processing.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Cells that utilize lateral inhibition appear primarily in the cerebral cortex and thalamus and make up lateral inhibitory networks (LINs).
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Artificial lateral inhibition has been incorporated into artificial sensory systems, such as vision chips, hearing systems, and optical mice.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] This phenomenon is thought to aid in colour discrimination.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The concept of neural inhibition (in motor systems) was well known to Descartes and his contemporaries.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Sensory inhibition in vision was inferred by Ernst Mach in 1865 as depicted in his mach band.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Inhibition in single sensory neurons was discovered and investigated starting in 1949 by Haldan K.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Hartline when he used algorithms to express the effect of Ganglion receptive fields.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] His algorithms also help explain the experiment conducted by David H.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Hubel and Torsten Wiesel that expressed a variation of sensory processing, including lateral inhibition, within different species.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] In 1956, Hartline revisited this concept of lateral inhibition in horseshoe crab (*Limulus polyphemus*) eyes, during an experiment conducted with the aid of Henry G Wagner and Floyd Ratliff.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Hartline explored the anatomy of ommatidia in the horseshoe crab because of their similar function and physiological anatomy to photoreceptors in the human eye.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Also, they are much larger than photoreceptors in humans, which would make them much easier to observe and record.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Hartline contrasted the response signal of the ommatidium when a single concentrated beam of light was directed at one receptor unit as opposed to three surrounding units.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] He further supported his theory of lateral inhibition as the response signal of one unit was stronger when the surrounding units were not exposed to light.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Georg von Békésy, in his book *Sensory Inhibition*, explores a wide range of inhibitory phenomena in sensory systems, and interprets them in terms of sharpening.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Lateral inhibition increases the contrast and sharpness in visual response.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] This phenomenon already occurs in the mammalian retina.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] In the dark, a small light stimulus will enhance the different photoreceptors (rod cells).
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The rods in the center of the stimulus will transduce the "light" signal to the brain, whereas different rods on the outside of the stimulus will send a "dark" signal to the brain due to lateral inhibition from horizontal cells.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] This contrast between the light and dark creates a sharper image.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] (Compare unsharp masking in digital processing).
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] This mechanism also creates the Mach band visual effect.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Visual lateral inhibition is the process in which photoreceptor cells aid the brain in perceiving contrast within an image.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Electromagnetic light enters the eye by passing through the cornea, pupil, and the lens (optics).
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] It then bypasses the ganglion cells, amacrine cells, bipolar cells, and horizontal cells in order to reach the photoreceptors rod cells which absorb light.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The rods become stimulated by the energy from the light and release an excitatory neural signal to the horizontal cells.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The central rod will send the light signals directly to bipolar cells which in turn will relay the signal to the ganglion cells.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Amacrine cells also produce lateral inhibition to bipolar cells and ganglion cells to perform various visual computations including image sharpening.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The final visual signals will be sent to the thalamus and cerebral cortex, where additional lateral inhibition occurs.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Sensory information collected by the peripheral nervous system is transmitted to specific areas of the primary somatosensory area in the parietal cortex according to its origin on any given part of the body.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] For each neuron in the primary somatosensory area, there is a corresponding region of the skin that is stimulated or inhibited by that neuron.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The regions that correspond to a location on the somatosensory cortex are mapped by a homunculus.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] This corresponding region of the skin is referred to as the neuron's receptive field.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The most sensitive regions of the body have the greatest representation in any given cortical area, but they also have the smallest receptive fields.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The lips, tongue, and fingers are examples of this phenomenon.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Each receptive field is composed of two regions: a central excitatory region and a peripheral inhibitory region.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] One entire receptive field can overlap with other receptive fields, making it difficult to differentiate between stimulation locations, but lateral inhibition helps to reduce that overlap.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] When an area of the skin is touched, the central excitatory region activates and the peripheral region is inhibited, creating a contrast in sensation and allowing sensory precision.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The person can then pinpoint exactly which part of the skin is being touched.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] In the face of inhibition, only the neurons that are most stimulated and least inhibited will fire, so the firing pattern tends to concentrate at stimulus peaks.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] This ability becomes less precise as stimulation moves from areas with small receptive fields to larger receptive fields, e.g. moving from the fingertips to the forearm to the upper arm.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Similarities between sensory processes of the skin and the auditory system suggest lateral inhibition could play a role in auditory processing.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The basilar membrane in the cochlea has receptive fields similar to the receptive fields of the skin and eyes.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Also, neighboring cells in the auditory cortex have similar specific frequencies that cause them to fire, creating a map of sound frequencies similar to that of the somatosensory cortex.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Lateral inhibition in tonotopic channels can be found in the inferior colliculus and at higher levels of auditory processing in the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] However, the role that lateral inhibition plays in auditory sensation is unclear.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Some scientists found that lateral inhibition could play a role in sharpening spatial input patterns and temporal changes in sensation, others propose it plays an important role in processing low or high tones.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Lateral inhibition is also thought to play a role in suppressing tinnitus.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Tinnitus can occur when damage to the cochlea creates a greater reduction of inhibition than excitation, allowing neurons to become aware of sound without sound actually reaching the ear.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] If certain sound frequencies that contribute to inhibition more than excitation are produced, tinnitus can be suppressed.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Evidence supports findings that high-frequency sounds are best for inhibition and therefore best for reducing some types of tinnitus.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] In mustached bats, evidence supports the hypothesis that lateral inhibitory processes of the auditory system contribute to improved auditory information processing.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Lateral inhibition would occur in the medial and dorsal divisions of the medial geniculate nucleus of mustached bats, along with positive feedback.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] The exact functions of these regions are unclear, but they do contribute to selective auditory processing responses.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] These processes could play a role in auditory functioning of other mammals, such as cats.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] In embryology, the concept of lateral inhibition has been adapted to describe processes in the development of cell types.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Lateral inhibition is described as a part of the Notch signaling pathway, a type of cell–cell interaction.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Specifically, during asymmetric cell division one daughter cell adopts a particular fate that causes it to be copy of the original cell and the other daughter cell is inhibited from becoming a copy.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Lateral inhibition is well documented in flies, worms and vertebrates.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] In all of these organisms, the transmembrane proteins Notch and Delta (or their homologues) have been identified as mediators of the interaction.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Research has been more commonly associated with Drosophila, the fruit fly.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] Synthetic embryologists have also been able to replicate lateral inhibition dynamics in developing bacterial colonies, creating stripes and regular structures.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] A neuroblast with slightly more Delta protein on its cell surface will inhibit its neighboring cells from becoming neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/lateral-inhibition] In flies, frogs, and chicks, Delta is found in those cells that will become neurons, while Notch is elevated in those cells that become the glial cells.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] A **neural circuit** is a population of neurons interconnected by synapses to carry out a specific function when activated.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Multiple neural circuits interconnect with one another to form large scale brain networks.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Neural circuits have inspired the design of artificial neural networks, though there are significant differences.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Circuits in artificial neural networks have been researched as cognates to neural circuits.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Early treatments of neural networks can be found in Herbert Spencer's *Principles of Psychology*, 3rd edition (1872), Theodor Meynert's *Psychiatry* (1884), William James' *Principles of Psychology* (1890), and Sigmund Freud's Project for a Scientific Psychology (composed 1895).
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The first rule of neuronal learning was described by Hebb in 1949, in the Hebbian theory.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Thus, Hebbian pairing of pre-synaptic and post-synaptic activity can substantially alter the dynamic characteristics of the synaptic connection and therefore either facilitate or inhibit signal transmission.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In 1959, the neuroscientists, Warren Sturgis McCulloch and Walter Pitts published the first works on the processing of neural networks.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] They showed theoretically that networks of artificial neurons could implement logical, arithmetic, and symbolic functions.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Simplified models of biological neurons were set up, now usually called perceptrons or artificial neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] These simple models accounted for neural summation (i.e., potentials at the post-synaptic membrane will summate in the cell body).
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Later models also provided for excitatory and inhibitory synaptic transmission.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The connections between neurons in the brain are much more complex than those of the artificial neurons used in the connectionist neural computing models of artificial neural networks.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The basic kinds of connections between neurons are synapses: both chemical and electrical synapses.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The establishment of synapses enables the connection of neurons into millions of overlapping, and interlinking neural circuits.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Presynaptic proteins called neurexins are central to this process.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] One principle by which neurons work is neural summation – potentials at the postsynaptic membrane will sum up in the cell body.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] If the depolarization of the neuron at the axon hillock goes above threshold an action potential will occur that travels down the axon to the terminal endings to transmit a signal to other neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Excitatory and inhibitory synaptic transmission is realized mostly by excitatory postsynaptic potentials (EPSPs), and inhibitory postsynaptic potentials (IPSPs).
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] On the electrophysiological level, there are various phenomena which alter the response characteristics of individual synapses (called synaptic plasticity) and individual neurons (intrinsic plasticity).
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] These are often divided into short-term plasticity and long-term plasticity.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Long-term synaptic plasticity is often contended to be the most likely memory substrate.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Usually, the term "neuroplasticity" refers to changes in the brain that are caused by activity or experience.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Connections display temporal and spatial characteristics.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Temporal characteristics refers to the continuously modified activity-dependent efficacy of synaptic transmission, called spike-timing-dependent plasticity.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] It has been observed in several studies that the synaptic efficacy of this transmission can undergo short-term increase (called facilitation) or decrease (depression) according to the activity of the presynaptic neuron.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The induction of long-term changes in synaptic efficacy, by long-term potentiation (LTP) or depression (LTD), depends strongly on the relative timing of the onset of the excitatory postsynaptic potential and the postsynaptic action potential.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] LTP is induced by a series of action potentials which cause a variety of biochemical responses.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Eventually, the reactions cause the expression of new receptors on the cellular membranes of the postsynaptic neurons or increase the efficacy of the existing receptors through phosphorylation.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In some cells, however, neural backpropagation does occur through the dendritic branching and may have important effects on synaptic plasticity and computation.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] A neuron in the brain requires a single signal to a neuromuscular junction to stimulate contraction of the postsynaptic muscle cell.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In the spinal cord, however, at least 75 afferent neurons are required to produce firing.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This picture is further complicated by variation in time constant between neurons, as some cells can experience their EPSPs over a wider period of time than others.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] While in synapses in the developing brain synaptic depression has been particularly widely observed it has been speculated that it changes to facilitation in adult brains.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Neural connections are built and maintained primarily by glia.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Astrocytes, a type of glial cell, have been implicated for their influence on synaptogenesis.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The presence of astrocytes, in rat retinal ganglion cell (RGC) cultures, increased synaptic growth, suggesting that it plays role in the process.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Through signals between synapses and astrocytes, the number of synapses are regulated as neuronal circuits as they develop.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Additionally, they release proteins to maintain homeostatic plasticity for the entire circuit and the synapse itself.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Early life adversity (ELA) during critical periods of development can influence circuitry.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] People exposed to several adverse life events undergo changes in connectivity that shape fear perception and cognition.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In opposition to those with a lack of ELA, amygdala volume is lower which is associated with possible issues in emotional control.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Also, stress in youth can irreversibly modify previously existing connection between the hippocampus, medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC), and orbitofrontal cortex (OFC).
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The interactions between these brain regions are critical to proper cognitive function.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] ELA poses a risk to normal working memory, learning memory, and other executive functions by reconstructing circuitry.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] An example of a neural circuit is the trisynaptic circuit in the hippocampus.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Another is the Papez circuit linking the hypothalamus to the limbic lobe.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] There are several neural circuits in the cortico-basal ganglia-thalamo-cortical loop.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] These circuits carry information between the cortex, basal ganglia, thalamus, and back to the cortex.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The largest structure within the basal ganglia, the striatum, is seen as having its own internal microcircuitry.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Neural circuits in the spinal cord called central pattern generators are responsible for controlling motor instructions involved in rhythmic behaviours.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Rhythmic behaviours include walking, urination, and ejaculation.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The central pattern generators are made up of different groups of spinal interneurons.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] There are four principal types of neural circuits that are responsible for a broad scope of neural functions.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] These circuits are a diverging circuit, a converging circuit, a reverberating circuit, and a parallel after-discharge circuit.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Circuits can also be classified as forms of feedforward excitation, feedforward inhibition, lateral inhibition, and mutual inhibition.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Diverging and converging circuits are a type of feedforward excitation.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Feedforward excitation refers to the method of travel taken by neuronal signals.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] It involves a downstream transfer of information.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In a diverging circuit, one neuron synapses with a number of postsynaptic cells.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Each of these may synapse with many more making it possible for one neuron to stimulate up to thousands of cells.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This is exemplified in the way that thousands of muscle fibers can be stimulated from the initial input from a single motor neuron.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In a converging circuit, inputs from many sources are converged into one output, affecting just one neuron or a neuron pool.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This type of circuit is exemplified in the respiratory center of the brainstem, which responds to a number of inputs from different sources by giving out an appropriate breathing pattern.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] A reverberating circuit produces a repetitive output.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In a signalling procedure from one neuron to another in a linear sequence, one of the neurons may send a signal back to initiating neuron.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Each time that the first neuron fires, the other neuron further down the sequence fire again sending it back to the source.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This restimulates the first neuron and also allows the path of transmission to continue to its output.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] A resulting repetitive pattern is the outcome that only stops if one or more of the synapses fail, or if an inhibitory feed from another source causes it to stop.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This type of reverberating circuit is found in the respiratory center that sends signals to the respiratory muscles, causing inhalation.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] When the circuit is interrupted by an inhibitory signal the muscles relax causing exhalation.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This type of circuit may play a part in epileptic seizures.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In a parallel after-discharge circuit, a neuron inputs to several chains of neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Each chain is made up of a different number of neurons but their signals converge onto one output neuron.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Each synapse in the circuit acts to delay the signal by about 0.5 msec, so that the more synapses there are, the longer is the delay to the output neuron.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] After the input has stopped, the output will go on firing for some time.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This type of circuit does not have a feedback loop as does the reverberating circuit.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Continued firing after the stimulus has stopped is called *after-discharge*.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This circuit type is found in the reflex arcs of certain reflexes.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Different neuroimaging techniques have been developed to investigate the activity of neural circuits and networks.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The use of "brain scanners" or functional neuroimaging to investigate the structure or function of the brain is common, either as simply a way of better assessing brain injury with high-resolution pictures, or by examining the relative activations of different brain areas.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Such technologies may include functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), brain positron emission tomography (brain PET), and computed axial tomography (CAT) scans.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Functional neuroimaging uses specific brain imaging technologies to take scans from the brain, usually when a person is doing a particular task, in an attempt to understand how the activation of particular brain areas is related to the task.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In functional neuroimaging, especially fMRI, which measures hemodynamic activity (using BOLD-contrast imaging) which is closely linked to neural activity, PET, and electroencephalography (EEG) is used.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Connectionist models serve as a test platform for different hypotheses of representation, information processing, and signal transmission.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Lesioning studies in such models, e.g. artificial neural networks, where parts of the nodes are deliberately destroyed to see how the network performs, can also yield important insights in the working of several cell assemblies.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Similarly, simulations of dysfunctional neurotransmitters in neurological conditions (e.g., dopamine in the basal ganglia of Parkinson's patients) can yield insights into the underlying mechanisms for patterns of cognitive deficits observed in the particular patient group.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Predictions from these models can be tested in patients or via pharmacological manipulations, and these studies can in turn be used to inform the models, making the process iterative.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The modern balance between the connectionist approach and the single-cell approach in neurobiology has been achieved through a lengthy discussion.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In 1972, Barlow announced the *single neuron revolution*: "our perceptions are caused by the activity of a rather small number of neurons selected from a very large population of predominantly silent cells." This approach was stimulated by the idea of grandmother cell put forward two years earlier.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Barlow formulated "five dogmas" of neuron doctrine.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Recent studies of 'grandmother cell' and sparse coding phenomena develop and modify these ideas.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The single cell experiments used intracranial electrodes in the medial temporal lobe (the hippocampus and surrounding cortex).
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Modern development of concentration of measure theory (stochastic separation theorems) with applications to artificial neural networks give mathematical background to unexpected effectiveness of small neural ensembles in high-dimensional brain.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Disruptions to neural circuitry caused by changes in neurons and neural networks can lead to the pathogenesis of mental illnesses and neurodegenerative diseases.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Modifications to the basal ganglia are often associated with diseases such as in Parkinson's disease.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Moreover, the elimination of dendritic spines in dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra and medium spiny neurons from the striatum which are located in the basal ganglia.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Methods like calcium imaging have identified dopamine receptors, D1 and D2, to be involved in the regulation of dendritic spine loss and formation.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] The removal of dendritic spine presence in neurons negatively impacts synaptic plasticity, learning, memory development, and overall cognitive function.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] In early stages of Alzheimer's disease and individuals with mild cognitive impairment, synaptic removal and alterations to typical dendritic spine structure have been observed.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Abnormalities to dendritic morphology include damage to neurites and spine loss.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] This can extend to the axon and trigger a progressive shrinking process.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Variations in the expression levels of Alzheimer's disease-related proteins include β-secretase, γ-secretase, and amyloid plaque also alter dendritic spine density.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-circuit] Closer proximity to these proteins further contributes to dendritic dissimilarities.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] In neuroanatomy, a **neural pathway** is the connection formed by axons that project from neurons to make synapses onto neurons in another location, to enable neurotransmission (the sending of a signal from one region of the nervous system to another).
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Neurons are connected by a single axon, or by a bundle of axons known as a nerve tract, or fasciculus.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Shorter neural pathways are found within grey matter in the brain, whereas longer projections, made up of myelinated axons, constitute white matter.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] In the hippocampus, there are neural pathways involved in its circuitry including the perforant pathway, that provides a connectional route from the entorhinal cortex to all fields of the hippocampal formation, including the dentate gyrus, all CA fields (including CA1), and the subiculum.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Descending motor pathways of the pyramidal tracts travel from the cerebral cortex to the brainstem or lower spinal cord.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Ascending sensory tracts in the dorsal column–medial lemniscus pathway (DCML) carry information from the periphery to the cortex of the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] The first named pathways are evident to the naked eye even in a poorly preserved brain, and were named by the great anatomists of the Renaissance using cadaver material.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Examples of these include the great *commissures* of the brain such as the corpus callosum (Latin, "hard body"; not to be confused with the Latin word "colossus" – the "huge" statue), *anterior commissure*, and *posterior commissure*.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Further examples include the pyramidal tract, crus cerebri (Latin, "leg of the brain"), and *cerebellar peduncles* (Latin, "little foot of the cerebellum").
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Note that these names describe the *appearance* of a structure but give no information on its function, location, etc.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Later, as neuroanatomical knowledge became more sophisticated, the trend was toward naming pathways by their origin and termination.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] For example, the nigrostriatal pathway runs from the substantia nigra (Latin, "black substance") to the corpus striatum (Latin, "striped body").
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] This naming can extend to include any number of structures in a pathway, such that the cerebellorubrothalamocortical pathway originates in the cerebellum, synapses in the red nucleus ("ruber" in Latin), on to the thalamus, and finally terminating in the cerebral cortex.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Sometimes, these two naming conventions coexist.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] For example, the name "pyramidal tract" has been mainly supplanted by lateral corticospinal tract in most texts.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Note that the "old" name was primarily descriptive, evoking the pyramids of antiquity, from the appearance of this neural pathway in the medulla oblongata.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] The "new" name is based primarily on its origin (in the primary motor cortex, Brodmann area 4) and termination (onto the alpha motor neurons of the spinal cord).
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] In the cerebellum, one of the two major pathways is that of the mossy fibers.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Mossy fibers project directly to the deep nuclei, but also give rise to the following pathway: mossy fibers → granule cells → parallel fibers → Purkinje cells → deep nuclei.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] The other main pathway is from the climbing fibers and these project to Purkinje cells and also send collaterals directly to the deep nuclei.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] In general, neurons receive information either at their dendrites or cell bodies.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] The axon of a nerve cell is, in general, responsible for transmitting information over a relatively long distance.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Therefore, most neural pathways are made up of axons.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] If the axons have myelin sheaths, then the pathway appears bright white because myelin is primarily lipid.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] If most or all of the axons lack myelin sheaths (i.e., are *unmyelinated*), then the pathway will appear a darker beige color, which is generally called *grey*.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Some neurons are responsible for conveying information over long distances.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] For example, motor neurons, which travel from the spinal cord to the muscle, can have axons up to a meter in length in humans.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] The longest axon in the human body belongs to the Sciatic Nerve and runs from the great toe to the base of the spinal cord.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] These are archetypal examples of neural pathways.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Neural pathways in the basal ganglia in the cortico-basal ganglia-thalamo-cortical loop, are seen as controlling different aspects of behaviour.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] This regulation is enabled by the dopamine pathways.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] It has been proposed that the dopamine system of pathways is the overall organiser of the neural pathways that are seen to be parallels of the dopamine pathways.
[src:neural-circuits/neural-pathway] Dopamine is provided both tonically and phasically in response to the needs of the neural pathways.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Major neuromodulators in the central nervous system include: dopamine, serotonin, acetylcholine, histamine, norepinephrine, nitric oxide, and several neuropeptides.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Cannabinoids can also be powerful CNS neuromodulators.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Neuromodulators can be packaged into vesicles and released by neurons, secreted as hormones and delivered through the circulatory system.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] A neuromodulator can be conceptualized as a neurotransmitter that is not reabsorbed by the pre-synaptic neuron or broken down into a metabolite.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Some neuromodulators end up spending a significant amount of time in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), influencing (or "modulating") the activity of several other neurons in the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The major neurotransmitter systems are the noradrenaline (norepinephrine) system, the dopamine system, the serotonin system, and the cholinergic system.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Drugs targeting the neurotransmitter of such systems affect the whole system, which explains the mode of action of many drugs.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Most other neurotransmitters, on the other hand, e.g. glutamate, GABA and glycine, are used very generally throughout the central nervous system.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The noradrenaline system consists of around 15,000 neurons, primarily in the locus coeruleus.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] This is diminutive compared to the more than 100 billion neurons in the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] As with dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra, neurons in the locus coeruleus tend to be melanin-pigmented.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Noradrenaline is released from the neurons, and acts on adrenergic receptors.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Noradrenaline is often released steadily so that it can prepare the supporting glial cells for calibrated responses.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The dopamine or dopaminergic system consists of several pathways, originating from the ventral tegmentum or substantia nigra as examples.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Parkinson's disease is at least in part related to dropping out of dopaminergic cells in deep-brain nuclei, primarily the melanin-pigmented neurons in the substantia nigra but secondarily the noradrenergic neurons of the locus coeruleus.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Treatments potentiating the effect of dopamine precursors have been proposed and effected, with moderate success.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The serotonin created by the brain comprises around 10% of total body serotonin.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The majority (80-90%) is found in the gastrointestinal (GI) tract.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] It travels around the brain along the medial forebrain bundle and acts on serotonin receptors.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] In the peripheral nervous system (such as in the gut wall) serotonin regulates vascular tone.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Although changes in neurochemistry are found immediately after taking these antidepressants, symptoms may not begin to improve until several weeks after administration.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Increased transmitter levels in the synapse alone does not relieve the depression or anxiety.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The cholinergic system consists of projection neurons from the pedunculopontine nucleus, laterodorsal tegmental nucleus, and basal forebrain and interneurons from the striatum and nucleus accumbens.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] It is not yet clear whether acetylcholine as a neuromodulator acts through volume transmission or classical synaptic transmission, as there is evidence to support both theories.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Acetylcholine binds to both metabotropic muscarinic receptors (mAChR) and the ionotropic nicotinic receptors (nAChR).
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The cholinergic system has been found to be involved in responding to cues related to the reward pathway, enhancing signal detection and sensory attention, regulating homeostasis, mediating the stress response, and encoding the formation of memories.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) has an inhibitory effect on brain and spinal cord activity.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] GABA is an amino acid that is the primary inhibitory neurotransmitter for the central nervous system (CNS).
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] It reduces neuronal excitability by inhibiting nerve transmission.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] GABA has a multitude of different functions during development and influences the migration, proliferation, and proper morphological development of neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] It also influences the timing of critical periods and potentially primes the earliest neuronal networks.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] There are two main types of GABA receptors: GABAa and GABAb.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] GABAa receptors inhibit neurotransmitter release and/or neuronal excitability and are a ligand-gated chloride channel.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] GABAb receptors are slower to react due to a GCPR that acts to inhibit neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] GABA can be the culprit for many disorders ranging from schizophrenia to major depressive disorder because of its inhibitory characteristics being dampened.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Neuropeptides are small proteins used for communication in the nervous system.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Neuropeptides represent the most diverse class of signaling molecules, and vary considerably between animals.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] There are 90 known genes that encode human neuropeptide precursors.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] In the fruit fly *Drosophila* there are ~50 known genes encoding precursors, and in the worm *C. elegans* 120 genes specify more than 250 neuropeptides.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Most neuropeptides bind to G-protein coupled receptors, however some neuropeptides directly gate ion channels or act through kinase receptors.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Neuromodulators may alter the output of a physiological system by acting on the associated inputs (for instance, central pattern generators).
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] However, modeling work suggests that this alone is insufficient, because the neuromuscular transformation from neural input to muscular output may be tuned for particular ranges of input.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] (2007) suggest that neuromodulators must act not only on the input system but must change the transformation itself to produce the proper contractions of muscles as output.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Neurotransmitter systems are systems of neurons in the brain expressing certain types of neurotransmitters, and thus form distinct systems.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Activation of the system causes effects in large volumes of the brain, called **volume transmission**.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Volume transmission is the diffusion of neurotransmitters through the brain extracellular fluid released at points that may be remote from the target cells with the resulting activation of extra-synaptic receptors, and with a longer time course than for transmission at a single synapse.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Such prolonged transmitter action is called **tonic transmission**, in contrast to the **phasic transmission** that occurs rapidly at single synapses.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] There are three main components of tonic transmission: Continued release, sustained release, and baseline regulation.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] In the context of neuromodulation, continuous release is responsible for releasing neurotransmitters/neuromodulators at a constant low level from glial cells and tonic active neurons.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Sustained Influence provides long-term stability to the entire process, and baseline regulation ensures that the neurons are in a continued state of readiness to respond to any signals.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Acetylcholine, noradrenaline, dopamine, norepinephrine, and serotonin are some of the main components in tonic transmission to mediate arousal and attention.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] There are three main components of phasic transmission: burst release, transient effects, and stimulus-driven effects.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] As the name suggests, burst release is in charge of releasing neurotransmitters/neuromodulators in intense, acute bursts.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Transient effects create acute momentary adjustments in neural activity.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Lastly, as the name suggests, stimulus-driven effects react to sensory input, external stressors, and reward stimuli, which involve dopamine, norepinephrine, and serotonin.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The term Neuromodulation is also known in medicine as a targeted artificial modification of neuronal activity through the delivery of chemical agents or electroceutical stimulation to specific neurological parts (see more in the wikiarticle Neuromodulation (medicine)).
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Invasive and non-invasive treatment methods form a field of medicine called neurotherapy.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] There are two main categories for neuromodulation therapy: chemical and electroceutical.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Electrical neuromodulation has three subcategories: deep brain, spinal cord, and transcranial, each aiming to treat specific conditions.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Deep brain stimulation involves electrodes being surgically implanted into specific sections of the brain that are commonly responsible for movement and motor control deficiencies and disorders like Parkinson's and tremors.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Spinal cord stimulation works by being placed near the spinal cord to send electrical signals through the body to treat various forms of chronic pain like lower back pain and CRPS.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] This form of neuromodulator treatment is considered one of the more high-risk treatments because of its manipulation near the spinal cord.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Transcranial magnetic stimulation is slightly different in that it utilizes a magnetic field to generate electrical currents throughout the brain.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] This treatment is widely used to remedy various mental health conditions like depression, obsessive-compulsive disorder, and other mood disorders.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Neuromodulation is often used as a treatment mechanism for moderate to severe migraines by way of nerve stimulation.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] These treatments work by utilizing the basic ascending pathways.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Electrical nerve stimulation and some of the characterizations include transcranial alternating stimulation and transcranial direct current stimulation.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] The other is magnetic stimulation, which includes single pulse and repetitive transcranial stimulation.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Chemical neuromodulation mostly consists of collaborating natural and artificial chemical substances to treat various conditions.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] It uses both invasive and non-invasive modes of treatment, including pumps, injections, and oral medications.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] This mode of treatment can be used to manage immune responses like inflammation, mood, and motor disorders.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Recent research has expanded mechanistic models of transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) beyond a strictly neuron-centered framework.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] Evidence suggests that tDCS influences multiple components of the neurovascular unit, including glial cells such as astrocytes and microglia, blood–brain barrier function, and neurovascular coupling.
[src:neural-circuits/neuromodulation] These interactions may contribute to long-lasting neuroplastic and behavioral effects observed following stimulation, indicating that tDCS outcomes are mediated by coordinated neuronal, glial, and vascular processes rather than direct neuronal polarization alone.
